Hygieia Team,
 Here is the background: I'm running the UI in a windows box and api and all other components in a Linux host. I have got UI and api talking - I'm able to login, create a dashboard.

while setting up code repo using the following options, the Save button doesn't seem to be doing anything.

Here is what I have provided as input for the widget based on your setup instructions at http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/getting_started.html

In the SCM panel, select 'git'
  b. Enter the URL: 'https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia.git' (without the quotes)
  c. Set the branch to 'master' (without the quotes)

As the other two parameters are optional, I didn't enter them.

Now if I hit 'Save', nothing happens. 

Can you please explain what is the problem here and how I can resolve it

column2:
This PR introduces **no** functionality changes, merely some cleanup.

During some updates to the gitlab scm collector, the name was changed from "gitlab-git" to "gitlab-scm", but some of the occurrences were overlooked. This PR ensures things are all matching regarding the name of the gitlab scm collector.

column2:
Changes:
1. Collector Item and Collector has CollectionErrors. Collectors must set it by catching exceptions.
2. After a certain threshold (configurable in settings) collector stops collecting for the collector item.
3. UI widget indicates if collector item has errors. Errors are cleared when the widget config is saved again
4. Also, fixed an issue with SCM collector item creation - every time there was a "save" config, it was creating a new collector item. Needed to create some custom repository query to find collector item matches via partial list of options. 

Resolves https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1339

column2:
@tabladrum @rob-miller-777 
In terms of securing APIs with some sort of token do you think this is a valid approach?

When an external system wants to make a call to a secure API in hygieia, the hygieia admin could generate a JWT token for them. The input for creating the token would be some identifier (key) and an expiration date. We wouldn't store the JWT token in hygieia, but we would store the identifier and the expiration date to have a record that a JWT token was issued to the calling system.

The calling system would pass in the token in the header of their call. We would decode the token to see its component parts that would give us the identifier.

A JWT token isn't really meant to be revoked, but at some point if we do wish to revoke the token we could use the "identifier" to somehow block it.
column5: Proposal: Securing APIs
column11:
301150797 @rob-miller-777 I agree ..its better to store API keys. I can merge https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1372 . Do you have something already in progress for the API keys? I have some screens now but they are JWT token creation based. satishc1
301151409 I don't have anything going for the API key stuff yet, all you. rob-miller-777
301153622 @rob-miller-777 No worries. I'll get that PR merged and re-work the token screens. satishc1
301154373 Sounds good, let me know when you have a pull request out there for the token stuff and I'll take a look. rob-miller-777
301280874 Closed. We will use api keys instead of a JWT token to secure the api. satishc1
301130723 I had considered using a JWT token, but I don't think that would be appropriate in this scenario.  JWT tokens are meant to have short life cycles, since they are valid until they expire, so I was thinking that we might want to take a different approach.  My thought would be to store API keys in the database, and check them on each request.  If we start to check JWT tokens to see if they have been revoked on each request, we lose the benefit of them being stateless. We could add something to the admin page to handle generating new api keys, and managing them there.  I created #1372 , nested routes, with the idea that we could really build out the admin functionality of the app.   rob-miller-777
301150797 @rob-miller-777 I agree ..its better to store API keys. I can merge https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1372 . Do you have something already in progress for the API keys? I have some screens now but they are JWT token creation based. satishc1

dbname=jiradb

 Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=localhost

 Database Port - default is 27017

 MongoDB replicaset

dbhostport=[host1:port1,host2:port2,host3:port3]

feature.epicQuery=epic

column2: This PR adds AD support. It also allows a dashboard to be owned by multiple users. This will enable standard users to assign their dashboard to their ldap id. The process for this will be to login to hygieia with your ldap id. This will create an entry in the user_info collection. Then login to hygieia with your standard id. Then assign the ldap id as an owner of your dashboard. Eventually you'll be able to turn off standard authentication and migrate hygieia to ldap.

300532749 @rob-miller-777 Let us think about this a little more... our initial thought was to list owners and the administrators on the RHS. The main use of this screen was to enable people to migrate their dashboards from the standard login to their ldap login. We will get feedback from people here as they start to use the screen.

I was also debating whether there is anyway to integrate the "Admin" screen that you created with this "Dashboard Admin" dialog ... off course currently there is no way to get to the "Admin" screen for non-admin users.
 satishc1
300535650 I think we should probably clarify the difference between an owner and an admin.  My thoughts would be an owner of a dashboard should have the ability to modify and delete the dashboards they are owners of.  An admin would have the same ability for every dashboard in the application, as well as controlling who other admins are, and other functionality we may want to give them in the future.  

Because of this, you would not want to integrate the admin page with the dashboard owner dialog, because they are completely different concepts.  The dashboard configuration dialog, in my opinion, should only be used to view and modify other owners of the dashboard you are looking at, having the admins incorporated as well becomes confusing because you really can't remove an admin from the RHS. rob-miller-777
300660759 @satishc1 @rob-miller-777  Both, sorry for confused the 'Admin'.  While I say 'admin', I mean the manger DN from our AD LDS service. We definitely need a manager authorization for the connection to our AD LDS service (refer to the Jenkins setting). There are many restriction settings apart from the manager DN, like we also need to set some 'Group Search Base', 'Group Search Filter' etc...

The process is like, when initially the connection to AD LDS is established, we need a manager DN with password to access the content where call a bind action. After successfully bind the manger account, we could then see the DN that we have....   Without bind the manager DN account, nothing is explored in the AD LDS servise.

Some more info pasted from ldp.exe console:

> ld = ldap_sslinit("XXX.XXX.XXXX.COM", 50001, 1);
Host supports SSL, SSL cipher strength = 128 bits
Established connection to XXX.XX.XXXX.COM.
Retrieving base DSA information...
Result <0>: (null)
Matched DNs: 
Getting 1 entries:
>> Dn: 
	1> currentTime: 5/11/2017 9:48:32 China Standard Time China Daylight Time; 
	......
-----------
res = ldap_bind_s(ld, NULL, &NtAuthIdentity, 1158); // v.3
	{NtAuthIdentity: User='s.xxx.xxxx'; Pwd= <unavailable>; domain = 'TEN'.}
Authenticated as dn:'s.xxx.xxxx'.

  xpdable
300818995 You currently can't pass those manager credentials in, however, it would take much to make that possible. There are two different issues being discussed here, the UI for adding new owners, and being able to integrate with AD using manager credentials.  rob-miller-777
300958244 @rob-miller-777 Thanks. I am talking about second issue. xpdable
300192447 @tabladrum LGTM satishc1
300372243 @rob-miller-777 @satishc1  Regarding the connection to our AD with Admin user/password setting, this does not work for that, does it?
Where I mean the setting like we did in Jenkins.
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/2903719/25883577/5093dcde-357e-11e7-83e1-2bbde322f0b5.png)

300491107 @xpdable You shouldn't need an admin user/password setting. Try it setting it up based on the auth.AD properties in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/README.md

column2: After working on the login and admin page a bit, I thought we could benefit from having a router in the app that provides nested views and routes.  Angular's routing module, "ngRoute" doesn't provide that, however "ui-router" does.  This pull request has the necessary changes to move over to the more powerful ui-router module with no functionality changes.  If approved, we could utilize this router to clean up the code throughout the app, and reduce code duplication such as how the navbar header is currently placed in pages.

column2:
The Hygieia Jenkins collector retrieves build data successfully upon initial configuration for pipeline jobs, but subsequently fails to retrieve new build information for those pipeline jobs previously configured. Non-pipeline jobs seem to retrieve new build information successfully. Seems similar to issue #1332

To reproduce:

1) Configure pipeline and non-pipeline jobs in Jenkins.
2) Configure Hygieia to retrieve Jenkins build data for jobs.
3) Execute Jenkins jobs.
4) Observe updates for non-pipeline jobs, but not for pipeline jobs.
column5: Jenkins collector not retrieving new build data for pipeline jobs

column2:
Wanted to throw out some ideas to get opinions.

## Current Implementation, user "admin" always admin:
### Description:
"Standard" user with username "admin" will always get admin privileges, so first person to create that account gets admin.
### Pros:
- Always an admin
### Cons:
- First person to create account gets admin
- Can't ever take away the admin users admin privileges
- Have to have Standard Authentication enabled to add other admins
- Solution is very hacky

## Alternate 1, first account created admin:
### Description:
The first user added to the UserInfo collection would get the admin role.
### Pros:
- Easy to enable
- Works for both Ldap or Standard
### Cons:
- If users already exist, no admin account will be created

## Alternate 2, admin account created by app on app startup if not existing
### Description:
When the application starts up, will check to see if an admin account exists, if there isn't one, one would be created.
### Pros:
- Would guarantee an admin account exists
- Works even if users already exist
### Cons:
- Would have to display admin account credentials in logs or something
- Would have to have standard login enabled

## Alternate 3, admin user account in application properties
### Description:
We could add new properties to the application properties for creating an admin account if it's not already there.
### Pros:
- Works even if users already exist
- Can always add new admins
### Cons:
- Admin account credentials in a props file
- Requires standard login enabled

## Alternate 4, next login if no admins is admin account
### Description:
If no admin accounts exist, the next account to login would get the admin role.
### Pros:
- Guarantees admin account
- Works for standard or ldap
### Cons:
- Have to check to see if admins exist on every login
- Race to see who logs in first after change made

column2: This pull request would make the authentication providers configurable.  By default, the only authentication provider would be the "Standard" hygieia authentication.  You can also choose to have both LDAP and Standard, or just LDAP.  This was created because we wanted to only give our users the choice of LDAP authentication.  It is also useful for organizations that don't utilize ldap because you can just hide that option from being shown.  Not only does this pull request hide these authentication methods on the UI, but also prevents them from being used to authenticate on the API as well.

column2:
This is a proposal for a new "Multi-team" dashboard that acts as a normal team dashboard with N number of components. It could be implemented two ways - (1) as simply an aggregation of existing team dashboards, or (2) as a fully configurable dashboard with each dropdown/selection allowing multiple collector items.

I have had a number of requests for a dashboard view that reports on multiple components at once. The goal would be to show all of the data normally found on a team dashboard in an aggregated way. For example:
- The feature widget would be able to include multiple teams / projects at once.
- The code repo widget would show multiple lines in the graph (one for each repo) with statistics on max and average commit counts
- The build widget would show multiple lines in the graph (one for each job). Average build duration could show histograms for each day. Latest builds could be over all jobs.
- The quality widget would show statistics on all components. Some, like the code coverage metric, could use percentiles (10th, 25th, 50th,
 75th, 90th) represented in some graphical form to best show data from multiple components.
- The monitor widget could allow for logical groupings of monitors
- The deploy widget would show a union of all of the unique environments. When entering the detailed view all of the components would be shown in a list.

The pipeline widget would show all of the components (#1259)

The goal is to better support highly componentized applications (such as by use of micro-services) while still being able to show the data in a single view intended to be consumed by developers. The product dashboard doesn't quite fit this use case because it is more of a "metrics" dashboard. Furthermore it's quite difficult to get set up (look at all the github issues raised by it) and has a number of issues.
column5: Proposal: Multi-team dashboard

column2:
This widget was skipped when changes were made to other widgets to convert them to use the uib-typeahead directive (#1049). This PR changes the deploy widget to use the typeahead mechanism. It works with or without the "aggregateServer" option. I also fixed an XLD bug while in here.

When aggregate servers is on it obtains data using the following algorithm:
```
        /*
         * Obtains deployment jobs using recursion when necessary. 
         * 
         * It is necessary to make additional calls when 'aggregateServers' is true since we need all like applications on different servers 
         * to be available when saving our data. To do this we compare the last item in the list from our first paged call to all subsequent data.
         * If the application name and id is the same then we keep the data in our list. Once we encounter data that is different we can cease recurision
         * since the calls are sorted.
         * 
         * Example:
         * Suppose a size of 3 is used with aggregate servers and our first REST call returns the following:
         *   Deployment A (http://deploy.instance1.com)
         *   Deployment A (http://deploy.instance2.com)
         *   Deployment B (http://deploy.instance1.com)
         *   
         * We need to make an additional rest call to see if there are any more 'Deployment B' jobs. Suppose the second REST call returns the following:
         *   Deployment B (http://deploy.instance2.com)
         *   Deployment B (http://deploy.instance3.com)
         *   Deployment C (http://deploy.instance1.com)
         *   
         * We will keep the Deployment B's returned from the REST call and ignore everything that comes after it. Since the last item in this list is different
         * than the name + id (not shown) for our original REST call we cease searching for more items.
         */
```
column5: (Performance Fix) Change deploy widget to use uib-typeahead

299242029 @rob-miller-777 
I'm ok with hard-coding admin to be the admin user. This could be setup feature where we add admin during the initial install.

The add/removing admins screen is not working right. What I'm seeing is I can add the users in any order. But while removing, it seems to be hard-coded to stop when there's one entry left in the list..regardless of who that last user might be.

We should probably exclude the "current" user from the LHS (or disable the button for the current user). satishc1
299249622 That is working as intended, there is some logic in the UI that hides the button if there is only one admin user left.

As far as disabling the button for current user, do you not want admins to be able to modify their own privilege?  rob-miller-777
299266539 @rob-miller-777 I was not concerned with admins being able to modify their own privilege. My concern was the admin can't remove the last user from the RHS. But playing around with it, I can see there is a workaround. Add the "admin" to the RHS, then remove the rest.
 satishc1
299274766 @tabladrum LGTM satishc1
299275679 Exactly, and once we figure something out so the "admin" user isn't always admin, it will make more sense. rob-miller-777

@rob-miller-777 @MarkRx @tabladrum I noticed a few things..

- How do we create the initial admin user? Just sign up ? Create in mongo ?

- The user_info collection doesn't specify that the admin user has ROLE_ADMIN in its authorities. How is the app identifying that the admin user is indeed an admin without having the role?

- On the Manage Admins screen, looks like it doesn't let you remove the last entry from the right hand side. And if I add and remove the "admin" user, does it affect anything?
 satishc1
299234687 Yeah, all these issues are related and are based on your first point, how do you create the first admin user?  To have an initial admin user, there is some logic in there that ensures the "standard" user with username "admin"  is always admin. [See here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1354/files#diff-714ec0af3e35cc9d1dd046a3e82efbb4)  This is a hack, and should be replaced by something better, but I didn't want to tackle that in this merge request, and it's how it currently works, so wasn't really changing anything.  So I do agree this needs to be addressed, just not sure how to handle it yet.

As far as removing admins, I don't allow you to remove the last admin because then you would be in trouble, and currently, removing the admin privilege from the "standard" user named "admin" won't have any effect as that user will always have admin privileges.    rob-miller-777

For api module

 ritusingh16
307931990 @nireeshT, @satishc1 - 
_*It would seem that the requied `key` property is never built/created in `dashboard.properties` for the running API component to ingest.*_ Do you concur? 

Looking at [properties-builder.sh](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/docker/properties-builder.sh) file for the API component, it is and _always_ has been missing a line to create a property named `key`, which would get built from an environment variable injected during `docker run` (or `docker-compose up`) and placed into `dashboard.properties` just before the container performs its command of 
```
java -Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/./urandom -jar api.jar --spring.config.location=/hygieia/dashboard.properties
```

So if it's not established during docker run-time... how else should this runtime property get into the running spring boot app? Maybe there's some hidden or missing docs that explain this. If not, then the `properties-builder.sh` needs an update, to add the line:
```
KEY=${KEY:-}
```

Without this, in the UI, if someone tries to create a GitHub repo collector that is password protected, the [rest call](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/rest/EncryptionController.java#L25) to `/encryption/{message}` will just return `"ERROR"` giving a message of _Error encrypting password_

If somehow the GitHubRepo object is created in MongoDB with an empty or null password, [this logic](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/DefaultGitHubClient.java#L116)
```java
                 // decrypt password
		 String decryptedPassword = "";
		 if (repo.getPassword() != null && !repo.getPassword().isEmpty()) {
		 	try {
		 		decryptedPassword = Encryption.decryptString(
		 				repo.getPassword(), settings.getKey());
		 	} catch (EncryptionException e) {
		 		LOG.error(e.getMessage());
		 	}
		 }
```
Will continue to pass along that empty or null password, which will resulting in requests sent to `getCommits` from the repo failing. 

Also the linked issue above suggest to look at these docs: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/README.md#encryption-for-private-repos

But, it refers to `api.properties` when it seems that docker uses `dashboard.properties`
 kwhickey
308556575 @ritusingh16, @nireeshT, @satishc1 
I found a decent workaround for this. Spring and its [property source precedence](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/reference/html/boot-features-external-config.html) allows for it to pick up config properties from various places, including the environment. 

So, while the `key` property is not declared anywhere as a placeholder in a properties file or in the `properties-builder.sh`  (and it should be), you can inject its value into the container as an environment variable, and spring will pick it up and use it.

Example snippet from `docker-compose.override.yml`:
```yaml
hygieia-api:
  environment:
    - JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_PASSWORD=hygieiasecret
    - AUTH_SECRET=********
    - KEY=********
```

Could really use some gap-filling in the docs to cover this option though, or to clarify the intended approach. kwhickey

column2:
AFAICT, the current Github collection only uses a username / password transmitted as HTTP Basic Auth (even over plaintext connections if specified :scream: ).

For many people (like us), this is a blocker as individual / system username / password details would not be allowed to be committed. Either way, programmatic access to private Github repositories would be best off using [their oAuth](https://developer.github.com/v3/oauth_authorizations/#create-a-new-authorization). In the simple case a [personal access token](https://github.com/settings/tokens/new) could be used, I believe. The advantage of course is that this can be controlled / revoked as seen fit by the user.

I couldn't find an existing ticket around this - has it been discussed?
column5: Github collector: support oAuth authentication

column2: This pull request builds upon #1340 which is why it looks so big. It adds the ability to add new standard admin users from within the application itself. Even with this change, the "standard" user with username "admin" will still always be an admin.  This was because I wasn't sure of the best way to add the first admin user, so any thoughts on that would be appreciated.
column5: Standard Admin Management
s

column2:
@nireeshT had brought up using LDAP groups to control admin users in Hygieia in #1129 .  After discussing with our team, we thought this would be a better approach as well.  This pull request would take control of admins for LDAP users outside of Hygieia, and utilize LDAP groups instead.  You will now be able to set an LDAP group as a configuration property, that contains all of Hygieia admins.  So if I have an LDAP group named "hygieia_admins", I would set `auth.ldapAdminGroup=hygieia_admins`.

To make this functionality work, I moved the "roles" property from the UserInfo collection, to the Authentication collection.  This means that currently, the UserInfo collection doesn't really do anything, but in the future it could be used to save application specific configurations such as themes.  

Admin control for standard users would still need to be controlled within the app, and there is a pull request coming for that functionality shortly.  

Resolves #1326 as well.

I agree with MarkRk on the overhead piece.

Also we wanted to use the user_info collection to store additional attributes from ldap such as email address, full name etc.

Is there a reason why you removed the record that was getting created in the user_info collection when a standard or ldap user signs in  ... and can you revert this change? satishc1

This provides ease of use and flexibility. The problem with using LDAP/AD for permissions is that in a large corporation there could be a lot of overhead and processes in order to add/remove/manage users in LDAP/AD groups. This solution would not work for us. MarkRx

column2: Invalid credentials should be handled gracefully by the github collector and displayed on the dashboard. Currently the collector keeps polling with invalid credentials.
column5: Handle bad credentials for scm widget
column11:
300488968 @tabladrum Nice. 👍  That looks great. Is the errors erased when they re-save the widget? How about this one http://fontawesome.io/icon/ban/ ? satishc1
300496484 I like it. When the threshold is reached, can we also alert the user that it's no longer trying to collect that repo in addition to the error message?  And how would you get it started again?  The reason I ask is what if your entire instance of gitlab goes down, and it hits that threshold for everything, would be nice to just click a button to get it collecting again for each repo. rob-miller-777
301168573 This is what I am contemplating...
1. For now only Github needs this check. As the collector items are user created via the UI. Others are fetched by the collectors. 
2. Potentially others may run into the same issue - if job config changes etc. I have seen this in NexusIQ too. 
3. Each collector will have full control over what error condition to capture to "lock" the collection for that specific collector item.
4. Will implement this for Github  for now and carry it forward one collector at a time. The UI and API wont change. 
5. Next round will be to lock down the whole collector (in the same way) when there is a global connectivity issue (say Github is down) and create a new Collector management Admin page to manage the collectors and potentially collector items from that page.

Thoughts? tabladrum
301170473 Sounds good to me.  As far as the collector management admin page, I have been thinking it would be nice to have something like this for managing things like Jenkins/Sonar servers, instead of relying on properties files which require the application to be restarted to take effect.   rob-miller-777
301170973 @rob-miller-777 exactly. When @satishc1 is done with his work on that page, I will add this. tabladrum
296691712 Was thinking about this when working on the gitlab collector, need some way to show the user that there is an error, just not sure how to do it with what's currently available. rob-miller-777
297439154 @satishc1 @rob-miller-777  - Also we may need to halt collectors when there is an error. My opinion,  we have to set a flag(or a value) to mongo and check for collector status. Use the same flag to propagate as an error in UI, code should handle to catch exception and terminate the collectors when occurred.  Thoughts? nireeshT
297451011 Here is my design suggestion:
Set a flag in collectorItem indicating a potential bad "url" (including bad credential). Set it to true when encounter non 200 response multiple times (configurable via properties). Unset only via UI. Also, the UI widget should indicate that the "url" is encountering trouble. tabladrum
297451441 Potentially can set "enabled" flag on the collector item to false too- the flag is there today. Only to be modified from UI.  tabladrum
297452019 I don't know about halting the collector, at least with github/gitlab, you can get errors when the user misconfigures there repo, or using a private repo without providing credentials.  This would then stop all repos from being collected.  

My suggestion:
Create a new collection for "Dashboard Errors", which can be populated by any of the collectors.  Then add something in the UI for displaying the dashboard errors to the user.  There are probably other cases where things fail silently that we should be displaying to the users.    rob-miller-777
297452036 While you are at it - fix one more bug too: 
The SCM widget creates duplicate collector items. Can you fix that too :-) tabladrum
297458934 @rob-miller-777 The collector should stop polling a configured scm (collectorItem) as soon as it encounters an error. We could relax this rule if we can correctly identify the type of error. For example a network error is not reason enough to stop polling, but bad credentials or bad url is reason enough. satishc1
297480837 That would be easy enough for Gitlab, as both bad credentials, and bad url would result in a 404.  Even with that, it would still be worthwhile to alert the user so they can fix the problem.  rob-miller-777
297483643 @rob-miller-777 Definitely. We can read the flag on the collectorItem and update the status of the widget. The widget currently displays the time when the last poll happened. @nireeshT is familiar with this piece. The status could be right next to it. satishc1
300366871 @satishc1 @rob-miller-777 @nireeshT 
I have done some initial POC to capture collection error and display on the widget. 
Check this branch: https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/tree/issue-1139

-Added "error" as a list of a new error class to collectorItem. 
-Capturing collector's client exception and adding to the error list.
-Collector properties file will have a threshold value for number of errors. When this threshold is reached, collector stops collecting for that collector item.
- In UI: widget load function will return the errors in Promise. widget.js will handle that and display a "red dot" next to widget heading. A tooltip will show error. Example UI is here:
![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6014941/25882547/0306f710-3512-11e7-8c5d-82d5883fd326.png)

What do you think? tabladrum
300488968 @tabladrum Nice. 👍  That looks great. Is the errors erased when they re-save the widget? How about this one http://fontawesome.io/icon/ban/ ? satishc1
300496484 I like it. When the threshold is reached, can we also alert the user that it's no longer trying to collect that repo in addition to the error message?  And how would you get it started again?  The reason I ask is what if your entire instance of gitlab goes down, and it hits that threshold for everything, would be nice to just click a button to get it collecting again for each repo. rob-miller-777
301168573 This is what I am contemplating...
1. For now only Github needs this check. As the collector items are user created via the UI. Others are fetched by the collectors. 
2. Potentially others may run into the same issue - if job config changes etc. I have seen this in NexusIQ too. 
3. Each collector will have full control over what error condition to capture to "lock" the collection for that specific collector item.
4. Will implement this for Github  for now and carry it forward one collector at a time. The UI and API wont change. 
5. Next round will be to lock down the whole collector (in the same way) when there is a global connectivity issue (say Github is down) and create a new Collector management Admin page to manage the collectors and potentially collector items from that page.

Thoughts? tabladrum
301170473 Sounds good to me.  As far as the collector management admin page, I have been thinking it would be nice to have something like this for managing things like Jenkins/Sonar servers, instead of relying on properties files which require the application to be restarted to take effect.   rob-miller-777
301170973 @rob-miller-777 exactly. When @satishc1 is done with his work on that page, I will add this. tabladrum

294528747 I just tried to remove my own personal 2FA from gitlab, thinking it might be the issue, but that still produces the same error. vanjos
294532096 Remove the path setting, that is if you have a private gitlab instance where it could be located at something like "http://gitlabhost:8080/pathToGitlab".  And your repo would be something like "http://gitlabhost:8080/pathToGitlab/groupname/projectname". rob-miller-777
294532330 In your case, I am assuming your project is just at "http://gitlab.com/yourgroup/yourproject".  The path setting is not needed.   rob-miller-777
294555434 Yup, that did it. vanjos
428499305 > configuration for our repo's master branch with an API key from my account that has both the scopes

how you configure for repo master branch with API key and enable scopes?? nurhannankhairi
294526746 This original issue is okay now...

We are now seeing an issue with the actual collector.  Having followed the instructions on how to get this working (and including the correct application.properties --- below), we seem to not be able to reach our gitlab project (which is private, but definitely accessible at the URL listed in the logs).

I have created (in the UI) an installation and configuration for our repo's master branch with an API key from my account that has both the scopes enabled:

**Gitlab API Key (scopes)**
```
Scopes￼￼
X api Access your API
￼￼X read_user Read user information
```

**application.properties**
```

Note: passwords hidden
===========================================
#Database Name
dbname=dashboard
#Database HostName - default is localhost
dbhost=172.17.0.2
#Database Port - default is 27017
dbport=27017
#Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=db
#Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=****
#Collector schedule (required)
gitlab.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
#Gitlab host (optional, defaults to "gitlab.com")
gitlab.host=
#Gitlab protocol (optional, defaults to "http")

#Gitlab port (optional, defaults to protocol default port)
gitlab.port=
#Gitlab path (optional, defaults to no path)
gitlab.path=XXX

#Maximum number of days to go back in time when fetching commits
gitlab.commitThresholdDays=15
#Gitlab Instance using self signed certificate
gitlab.selfSignedCertificate=false

column2:
The sonarQube api /api/resources?format=json has default limit of 500 items ( https://jira.sonarsource.com/browse/SONAR-6584 ) which cause not all the projects are fetched. Unfortunately my target project is out of those first 500 items on the production SonarQube in the company:(

To work around , I added the desired project name on Line 38 of [DefaultSonarClient.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/build/sonar/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/DefaultSonarClient.java) for now :
`private static final String URL_RESOURCES = "/api/resources?format=json&resource=MYPROJECT";`
But, obviously it will and only will work for me if I only have this one project to be used in the dashboard.

As the limitation could not be eliminated. Could you:
1) Somehow bulk fetch ALL projects
or 
2) Add some configuration in the application properties to specify the desired project name:
like 

> sonar.project[0]=myproject1
sonar.project[1]=myproject2
...

and then to (only) fetch those projects in the list by  /api/resources?format=json&resource=myproject1 ...

column2:
As a power user of Hygieia
I want to have the ability to support rollups and weighted averages
So that I can visualize high level metrics composed of a collective of lower level metrics.

In the case of no weight specified the default behavior would be to assign a weight equally for the average.

Examples:
Production Defects: display the total number of defects for a product aggregated from features that make up the product
Performance Metrics: display performance as a higher level metric that is a weighted average of throughput, latency, and response times

297121395 This can probably be written better, but here is a quick hack to fix getProjects method.
`    
@Override
    public List<SonarProject> getProjects(String instanceUrl) {
        List<SonarProject> projects = new ArrayList<>();
        String url = instanceUrl + URL_RESOURCES;

        try {
            JSONObject jsonArray = parseAsObject(url);
            JSONArray otherArray = (JSONArray)jsonArray.get("components");

            for (Object obj : otherArray) {
                JSONObject prjData = (JSONObject) obj;

                SonarProject project = new SonarProject();
                project.setInstanceUrl(instanceUrl);
                project.setProjectId(str(prjData, ID));
                project.setProjectName(str(prjData, NAME));
                projects.add(project);
            }

        } catch (ParseException e) {
            LOG.error("Could not parse response from: " + url, e);
        } catch (RestClientException rce) {
            LOG.error(rce);
        }

        return projects;
    }

    private JSONObject parseAsObject(String url) throws ParseException {
        ResponseEntity<String> response = rest.exchange(url, HttpMethod.GET, this.httpHeaders, String.class);
        return (JSONObject) new JSONParser().parse(response.getBody());
    }
` jessepiccolo

`git.host=https://stash.******.com:7990`

Why the collector is trying to use 7999 when actual is 7990.

My rest api is absolutely working with the 7990 `https://stash.******.com:7990/rest/api/1.0/projects/devops/repos/sandbox/commits?until=master&limit=25` when i hit in browser.


Please advice.

column2:
The regular expression for parsing Story data is used on the toString() of a Jira Story. We have a custom field on our stories that allows multiline text (so \n in the text), which . will not normally match. Changing the regular expression to (?s).*\\[.+\\][^\\]]*(?-s) fixes this. ?s turns on DOTALL mode for Pattern.

I can submit a pull request soon for this change as I'm not setup for that right now, but here is a patch for it.

[regex_patch.txt](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/files/903915/regex_patch.txt)
column5: Update Story regular expression to allow . to match newlines

column2:
Added functionality to get all branches from a GitHub repository. 

Refactored some of the code:
    renamed getBranch as getDefaultBranch
    fixed typo: paresAsArray -> parseAsArray
    moved formatAPIUrl into new method


This can be used for further functionality such as allowing the user to dynamically choose which branch to show commits for instead of forcing them to choose a static branch when creating the SCM widget.
column5: Get all branches of a GitRepository
column11:
294865193 Are we not getting the commits from the other branches? tabladrum
294878321 Not in this PR. We don't need all the commits for each branch in our use case and wanted to get an idea of PR turnaround time before committing additional effort. MHudak
304075713 @MHudak Looks like there are a few compile errors due to merging other PRs. Please rebase. satishc1
305644090 @satishc1 @tabladrum  LGTM nireeshT
317824503 @MHudak @tabladrum Closing this PR because it doesn't align with the GitHubRepo model which currently works on a specific branch.

The recommendation is create a separate collection called gitmetadata.  This will be updated from GitHubCollectorTask. This is similar to gitrequests which contains pulls and issues and is updated from GitHubCollectorTask.

You can store repo level information inside the gitmetadata collection. Things you could choose to store in here includes branches, last time a branch was updated, releases, commits, contributors etc. The screenshots below show what could be captured.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/21199084/28586407-b03474d8-7141-11e7-960d-d866e76f50d8.png)

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/21199084/28586418-ba4077e2-7141-11e7-96bf-7ca6e3629ed7.png)

 satishc1

column2:
I have read the code to calculate the average time of code commit in each pipeline stage.
![average time](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24744685/7493817e-1ae5-11e7-8f86-e7eef3a063b7.png)
The code is between line 114 and 182 in js file UI\src\components\widgets\product\js\commit-data.js.
For example, in order to calculate the average time of Commit stage, it will calculate the time intervals of  Commit stage -> Prod stage, Commit stage-> QA stage, Commit stage -> DEV stage, Commit stage-> BUILD stage, and it will calculate the time intervals of all the code commit time to now in Commit pipeline stage, then calculate the average of all the time intervals, is this reasonable？ why?

Another issue, I think when calculate the average time of each pipeline stage, the order of all the stages should be Commit, Build, DEV, QA, Prod, but when I debug the code, the order is Build, Commit ~~~, the first one should be Commit not Build. 
![order](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24745541/a1e20c7e-1ae8-11e7-9160-ae34c13fbf2b.png)
column5: The average time of commit in each pipeline stage in product level dashboard make people puzzled.
column11:
292110861 It should be the average time of commit movement from previous stage to current stage, right? wdquan1985
292179229 @wdquan1985  - Order of stages in above code is irrelevant in above code because we maintain order of stages separately and that order is used for display on product dashboard.  nireeshT
292388785 @nireeshT - I create another team level dashboad with the same data as above but without deployment pipeline configured, add this new team dashboard to the product dashboard, the stages order is Commit, Build not Build, Commit.
![two stages](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24781598/5646c54e-1b73-11e7-8c05-80b5e877621d.png)

And the average time for Commit and  Build stages in the two team dashboard is different, but from the code above, they should be different.
![different](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24781630/8f435bdc-1b73-11e7-8ba4-268485cabc17.png)
 

 wdquan1985
292418268 @nireeshT - The dynamic pipeline code had been changed.
I use an example to show the change, we have three code commits 1, 2, 3, commit 1 has been deploied, commit 2 has been build.
Before the dynamic pipeline code change, pipeline will show as following.
![way 1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24784316/3db82796-1b84-11e7-9280-b95d6191bda7.png)

But after the code change, pipeline will show as following.
![way 2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24784321/4e184a58-1b84-11e7-8bbc-9c83f0d376fb.png)

The dynamic pipeline code has been changed, but the average time code not, is there any mismatch? wdquan1985
292551850 @wdquan1985  we do not go with the order shown above as the list will not guarantee the order of elements, so order is maintained separately in different object from Mongo. I am looking in to dynamic pipeline, looks like it need a fix or may be not. Will let you know.  nireeshT

column2:
Your **Logback Classic Module 1.1.3** library, a direct dependency in your **capitalone/Hygieia** repository, is subject to vulnerability [SID-3657: arbitrary code execution via serialization](https://www.sourceclear.com/registry/vulnerabilities/3657).

A direct dependency is a library that is specified in your project’s api/pom.xml.  A vulnerability in a direct dependency can be fixed by updating the version of the library in your project and rebuilding it.

This issue was fixed in version 1.2.0. However, that version may itself be subject to [other vulnerabilities](https://www.sourceclear.com/registry/libraries/434?version=1.2.0). We suggest that you upgrade to version 1.1.11, which is considered safe.

Be sure to build, test, and re-scan your project to ensure this fix has been successful.

##### api/pom.xml
```java
<dependency>
  <groupId>ch.qos.logback</groupId>
  <artifactId>1</artifactId>
  <version>1.1.11</version>
</dependency>
```

For more information on this vulnerability, please visit the [SourceClear Registry](https://www.sourceclear.com/registry/vulnerabilities/3657).
column5: Vulnerability in Logback Classic Module 1.1.3 of capitalone/Hygieia

column2: With the amount of potential tools available to integrate with Hygieia, it will probably be very difficult to manage at some point.  Have you guys given any thought to creating some sort of plugin architecture for Hygieia for adding new tools.  For instance, instead of having Gitlab, Github, SVN and Bitbucket available by default as SCM collectors, don't have any available until you "install" the plugin for the tool, however that may look.  I know it would be a significant effort, but it might be worth thinking about with all the potential tools available for integration.
column5: Hygieia Plugin Architecture
column11:
292593142 Possibly related: #1305 mrpudn
292595435 I like the idea too @amitmawkin @satishc1 @MarkRx  tabladrum
292604455 The only complaint I have with this approach is conflicts. If one plugin works on it's own but not with others or a combination thereof, it begins to get messy doing the cleanup afterwards which often never ends, and requires exponentially more tests to automate. SO as I do agree there would be benefit from a plugin architecture, the goal of any plugin should be to be fully integrated into the stable base as a feature. GNU is Not Unix.  swizzley
292613467 That's fair, our concern comes from the fact that we have some homegrown tooling that we would like to incorporate into Hygieia.  So obviously we wouldn't contribute collectors/UI changes back for these, since they wouldn't make sense outside our company. So that would leave us with a couple options, fork the repo, and make our specific changes to our fork. Or if plugins were possible, we could just write plugins for our custom stuff.    rob-miller-777
292988798 see [#1305](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1305) for a proposed solution to this swizzley

column2:
This PR will resolve #986, and will resolve #1224 

This PR enhances the monitor widget in three different ways:
* **UI Side**
  * It adds a new icon to denote services explicitly as unauthorized (this icon is a lock, and it is green due to the fact that in order to get the unauthorized the service must be on and running)
  * It adds a legend for quick explanations of what the different icons mean
* **API Side**
  * It adds support to apply proxy credentials via the API properties file to allow the ServiceService to ping endpoints outside of the proxy.

**Also Included**
* Slight refactor of how service health checks are made to make it more testable.
* Dashboard ID is passed to layer where call is being made - this ensures more informative logging around which dashboard is having connectivity issues and/or which dashboard is pinging endpoints it possibly should not be pinging.

Only functionality change is making the port optional if running in a docker build.  Before an empty string would be used if the port was not provided, causing an integer parse exception.  Now it won't try to add the port if it is blank.  

Other changes are just to make the code more consistent with other collectors and minor refactoring.

Do I have to specify my github username and password in github collectors properties file before generating key using core?
github.host=github.com
github.username=anuraXXXXX

No. In your github.properties you'll need
github.host=github.com

2nd you have mentioned api.properties but in your repo api.properties is not present

The properties file that you use to launch the api module = api.properties or whatever you named it.

3rd will it work with 12factor enable repos?

column2:
Question for the Hygieia community.  I have seen some issues posted here asking about the support for alternative datasources from MongoDB.  But, I was thinking of an alternative option from supporting alternative "datasource".

How much interest would there be for an enhancement to Hygieia that would enable collectors to send the data they collect to a configurable endpoint (e.g REST) in addition to going to MongoDB?  I was thinking this destination endpoint would be configured per collector.  The endpoint would be optional, so it is only executed if it is configured.

289827334 @satishc1 I saw the role of the endpoint as a way to share the data collection event preformed by Hygieia with systems external to Hygieia.  It is a notification that a particular data collection event took place and here is the data that was collected.  The system behind the endpoint could then do whatever it wants with the notification and data. ceytalis

column2:
I have spent the good part of the last two weeks playing around with the Jenkins Publisher.  It has been a bit of a struggle trying to figure out why I couldn't get commits to move from the build phase, to any of my environments, but I think I finally tracked it down.  The issue seems to stem from a recent change made for the dynamic pipeline.  (Sidenote, what is the need for having the standard pipeline, and the dynamic pipeline, and which should I be using?) I am currently using the standard pipeline.  The major problem seems to be when I have changes in the build env, and I run the deploy publisher, it tries to match to artifacts with the same artifact name and extension.  However, a recent change was made to the [DeployBuilder](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/commit/737e14e2354a9d1a0d70354e2b9c5ef488bc7eff) which pulls the version and extension out of the artifact name, instead of just the version.  This means that an artifact containing a change set will never match up to the environment, as the extension is always null, stranding the change sets in the build env forever.  Has anyone else encountered this issue?

@MarkRx @tabladrum

I see that the Jenkins build collector makes a rest call to Jenkins to get the instance jobs and returns the response json object with either the job or build details. 
How is the build data really made available as a result of the rest call from build collector?
Does the hygieialistener in the hygieia Jenkins plugin package intercepts this rest call and collects the build information and supplies it back?

I apologize if this is a novice question, please direct me to the post if this question is already answered.

I am in the process of collecting deploy data from Jenkins and I see this deploy data will be published from the listener on an overidden onCompleted method inside the listener, if deploy data is set to published in the plugin UI. I am currently getting only the build json response on the deploy job. I am expecting deploy json data as mentioned in the DeployDataCreateRequest.java dashboard model class in core api, not sure what step I am missing here
column5: How is jenkins hygieia plugin related to jenkins build collector
column11: 289139907 @alagus84 - When hygieia plugin is configured, hygieialistener wil push build and deploy data to MongoDB and supply it to UI. Looks like you have done a partial configuration of hygieia publisher on jenkins job. Follow screenshot and check deploy settings and rerun jenkins, that should push deply details to Mongo. nireeshT 289185032 I did configure the deploy job, but I will go back check if the configuration was correct or if I missed anything. I am slightly confused when you said hygieialistener will push build and deploy data to mongodb. I see following activity is done by Jenkins-build-collector 1. Hit mongodb to verify if the collector is present in the collector repository 2. Make a rest call to Get job count and the instance jobs from Jenkins by making recursive calls Jenkins, provided if there are subjobs 3. Hit Mongodb to get all the existing build jobs 4. Filter new jobs by comparing results from step 2 & 3 5. Add new job and build details to Mongo db So from the above step, I see Jenkins build collector collects the job and build data from Jenkins and pushes it to mongo db Following is what I see happening in Jenkins hygieia plugin 1) HygieiaListener has a lifecycle methods onstarted and oncompleted. onstarted publishes build data and oncompleted publishes build, artifact, sonar, test results, and deploy data 2) publish build data makes a rest call to jenkins and publishes build information and publish deploy data makes a rest call to Jenkins to retrieve and publish deploy information First question is what is this listener configured to listen to? Second question, to whom are they publishing this information to? Thirdly, If Jenkins build collector retrieves the job and build data from Jenkins, reconciles and pushes the new job and build data to mongo db, what is the need to have a hygieia listener. Again I am sorry if I am confusing you, but I am trying to understand the very existence of hygieialistener and the duties it does. Probably if my above 3 question were answered, that would shed me some light to proceed further. Thanks for your help alagus84 289451789 @alagus84 - Hygieia publisher plugin configuration does collect build data and deploy data if you configure in jenkins job as mentioned in screenshot. Two ways you can collect build data - either by using Jenkins build collector or by configuring Hygieia publisher plugin in Jenkins job like screenshot above( use either one way but not both). I am assuming you are using Hygieia publisher plugin, your second post said otherwise. Deploy data can be collected - either using uDeploy collector or by configuring Hygieia publisher plugin(use either one). if you want to collect build and deploy data separately with different collectors, use Jenkins-build collector and uDeploy collector but not Hygieia publisher plugin. nireeshT 289780645 @alagus84 Closed. Reopen with screenshot or error log on a specific problem you are having. satishc1

column2:
resolves #1097 

Provided is an automated UI test suite using Serenity and jBehave. 

The solution has been dockerized for ease of injecting data and ensuring proper setup and tear down. (credit to @brennanananan)

* Tests can be run either locally or as a continuous integration step. (See readme for setup instructions).
* Test reports can be found in ${UI-tests}/target/site/serenity/index.html after the test suite has finished executing.
* Test data can be pre-inserted to the mongodb through the mongo_setup.js
* You may select your target webdriver based on the Selenium node image you choose.
* You are able to run tests on a UI deployed on an SSL server.

A note on completeness:
* This is merely a foundation for building a more robust UI test suite. It is out of the scope of this pull request to include tests for every feature of this product.
* As more features are developed, it will be easy for the contributor to add automated UI tests.

296674484  @brennanananan Thanks, I changed my Mozilla firefox browser version from 52 to 30. Now the UI-Tests run succesfully with the command : mvn clean install -DUITEST_EXISTING_USERNAME=hygieia_test_user -DUITEST_EXISTING_PASSWORD=password.

 As im not using docker, is there any option to cleanup the test data from mongodb once the test run is completed doraemon0011
296696228 @doraemon0011 Currently there is no way to easily clean up the database inside the UI test execution. The reason we preferred to use the docker solution was so that we could perform whatever operations on the database that we needed, and then simply stop the container at the end. In that scenario, cleanup is not needed as the data is never persisted outside of the container. brennanananan

I have added the hygieia-jenkins plugin in my jenkins. 
I would like to know what is the connectivity between the environments(dev,prod,qa) I specify in the plugin setup and the environments in the jenkins? I see there is no step to give the jenkins server in the plugin setup.

And also I would like to know how the environments are listed down in the "configure deploy widget" step.
I am not getting any environments in the dropdown.

Please clarify as soon as possible.
column5: Jenkins plugin- How to setup deploy widget?
column11: 289559382 artifactDirectory: '/app/target' Did the trick! Thanks. celamb4 289742949 The **Deployed** status is always **false** in the **environment_components** table. I am getting published deploy data: response code: 201 in jenkins pipeline console output. Because of this the deploy widget always be in red colour. 1. When the deployed status will change to **true**? 2. Server up count is always 0 in deploy widget. why? I also see there is no environment_status table getting generated. Satheesh-b 378672054 @Satheesh-b Hi Sateesh, I am facing the similar issue. My deployment status is always true. So the pipeline is always green and if i intentionally fail the job. There is no update in mongo db. Any idea how you resolved this . syedsfayaz 378718192 @syedsfayaz Try changing the buildStatus : "Failure" in hygieiaDeployPublishStep, if you have a condition to check the status of your deployment in pipeline and it reports that the deployment doesn't happen due to any reason. Satheesh-Balachandran 378738541 @Satheesh-b @nireeshT I was trying to manually modify the status and i see this error. ( do we have any status apart from passed and failed) db.environment_components.update({"_id" : ObjectId("5ac40ca105d8147f02b94d2b")},{$set:{"deployed" :InProgress}}) 2018-04-04T13:41:25.284-0700 E QUERY [thread1] ReferenceError: InProgress is not defined : @(shell):1:88 syedsfayaz 288720822 @Satheesh-b - make sure you give environment name in Hygieia publisher settings. Environment value is what displayed in deploy widget for the selected deploy job. Make sure Application name remains same for all the deploy jobs in different environments. Refer screenshot. nireeshT 288948871 @nireeshT thanks for the prompt reply. But where we are supposed to give the deployment environment URL(IP address) for each environment. How the plugin fetches the data from each environment without the URL? Currently, my plugin returns environment URL which is as same of the Jenkins URL(Referred from environment_components table). It should point to each deployment environment URL. I would like to know where I should give the environment URL in the configuration for each environment. Satheesh-b 289218385 Im also having a similar issue. Jenkins plugin is deployed, configured and connect to Hygieia successfully. I then integrated the hygieia pipeline steps within my groovy script. Here is my example for deploy step: `hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'App name', artifactDirectory: 'app/target', artifactGroup: 'com.yourcompany.product1', artifactName: '*.jar', artifactVersion: '0.0.1', buildStatus: 'Success', environmentName: 'DEV'` The pipeline finishes/passes but I'm not gettng a dropdown in the Hygieia deploy widget. celamb4 289451181 @Satheesh-b Please follow the steps listed in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/hygieia-jenkins-plugin/README.md on how to configure the plugin. And follow steps listed in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/884 on how to configure your deployment jobs. The hygieia plugin does not need to know any information about "deployment environment URL(IP address) for each environment" . Your jenkins deploy job takes care of that based on what you specify for the deploy and the post build step tells Hygieia about a "successful" deployment. satishc1 289453249 @Satheesh-b @celamb4 - Reopen if issue not resolved. nireeshT 289488208 @satishc1 Thanks for your reply. I have successfully configured the plugin and able to get the information from local jenkins. But our actual requirement is to display the deployment information for an application which resides in a remote server. How can I monitor an application deployed via jenkins into a remote server? In that case what would be the artifact directory? Satheesh-b 289502753 @Satheesh-b You can "monitor" a url using the monitor widget. The artifact directory is on the jenkins server that builds the artifact. Your deployment job needs to have steps (eg.shell, pipeline etc) in the deploy job to "send" the artifact to the environment in question. The hygieia plugin doesn't monitor the artifact end location. satishc1 289543467 @satishc1 Thank you for your reply. Just went over #884 not sure if I'm missing something since I'm still missing the data in the UI. 1. Hygieia jenkins plugin is configured and connects to hygieia api. 2. In my pipeline. I have added all steps from the hygieia plugin in their respected locations. For example, buildstatus, aritfact, deploy, etc. 3. I then go to the hygieia UI --> deploy widget but dont have any apps listed. Here is the example of my hygieia deploy step in the jenkins pipeline. `hygieiaDeployPublishStep applicationName: 'App name', artifactDirectory: 'app/target', artifactGroup: 'com.yourcompany.product1', artifactName: '*.jar', artifactVersion: '0.0.1', buildStatus: 'Success', environmentName: 'DEV'` Thanks again! celamb4 289552721 @celamb4 Assuming your artifact is being generated inside $yourjenkinsworkspace/app/target Try changing artifactDirectory: 'app/target' to be artifactDirectory: '/app/target' Verify that you have a jar file inside $yourjenkinsworkspace/app/target Try that and if still an issue, please post your jenkins job log. satishc1 289559382 artifactDirectory: '/app/target' Did the trick! column2:
Hello,

Can we deploy UI in microsoft IIS? I've created a website pointing to dist directory and started API component in 8888 port in same server. 
I am able to launch UI in browser but it is not connecting to API module. Tried url redirect and other ways in IIS to redirect :3000/api to :8888/api, still no luck.

Please help understand building/deploying UI component to work in IIS.

Thanks and Regards,
Srinivas

In order to use the ldap authentication function, I use the springSecurityIntergration https://github.com/StateFarmIns/Hygieia/tree/springSecurityIntegration.
The ldap authentication function works well, but the pipeline in the procuct level dashboard can't show.
![pipeline](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24136508/0c614d68-0e4a-11e7-8d78-8d32369b2d83.png)
column5: Spring security: pipeline in product level dashboard can't show when use the springSecurityIntergration branch.
column11:
289281073 @nireeshT - I had tried removing "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled" from properties, but it can't work as well as adding "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled". When remove it, assume that team dashboard 1 has pipeline stages data, add a new team dashboard 2, add the same build data and repo data to team dash 2, there will be no stages data of team dashboard 2. wdquan1985
289333222 @nireeshT, @MarkRx - I think the goal of pipeline is to see movement of each code commit through the different development stages – code commit, build, deployment to DEV, QA, INT etc. all the way to production. Each of these stages shows the number of commits waiting to go to the next stage – amplifying the wait-times between the stages.  wdquan1985
289757691 I have as of yet had time to go back and touch up the dynamic pipeline services to make it more robust. Basically the idea is to build the pipeline dynamically with the data on hand as opposed to building it when the data is added as this has a number of problems (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/804#issuecomment-247391585). Looks like that change you made adds in some missing logic that was added to the regular pipeline when custom names of environments were added. MarkRx
289970574 @MarkRx - My change only add prodStage and orderMap info in pipeline response, so the pipeline info can show in the product dash. Hope the whole dynamical pipeline function can work as soon as possible.

Thanks. wdquan1985
290134994 @wdquan1985  update to latest code base and check. Reopen if still issue.  nireeshT
288068373 @wdquan1985  - remove team dashboard from product dash, reconfigure pipeline widget and add it back. Make sure code repo and build widgets are configured as well.  nireeshT
288280399 @nireeshT , I configure the code repo and build widgets in their team level dashboard, remove team dashboard from product dash, and add it back, but still can't show pipeline.
![teamlevel](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24179520/877c1154-0eea-11e7-943e-a6c81ffcdf4e.png)
![productlevel](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24179524/8ef59a5e-0eea-11e7-8796-adff7b1658f4.png)
 And the pipeline data in mongo db has been produced.
![pipelines](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24179562/ceb44410-0eea-11e7-97b1-f4fe31962ec5.png)
 wdquan1985
288385285 @wdquan1985  - you configured pipeline widget with custom stage names ?  nireeshT
288591141 @nireeshT , I can't find anything, I can't find custom stage names.
![pipelineconfigure](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24227931/d24904be-0fab-11e7-9624-4a32943f7628.png)
Is there anything wrong in my application? 
 wdquan1985
288628241  @nireeshT - additional information to explain, I have not configured deployment widget, but I don't think it should affect the other stage, such as commit and build. 
And I add a configuration "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled" in application.properties for api, so when request for pipeline info, it use dynamic pipeline service, and the value of property orderMap will not be set when build pipeline response, but this property will be used in the product level dash to show all the pipeline stages, so there is no any stage shown. wdquan1985
288717939 @wdquan1985  - remove  "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled" and re run api. You should see COMMIT and BUILD. nireeshT
288761974 In order for the dynamic pipeline to work your git repo url must match what jenkins is reporting it is using. The branch must match as well. Turning on debug in the API should show you what is going on. MarkRx
288962401 @nireeshT , @MarkRx , I add the following code to the method buildPipelineResponse of DynamicPipelineServiceImpl.java file, it can work now.
        _pipelineResponse.setProdStage(PipelineUtils.getProdStage(dashboard));
        pipelineResponse.setOrderMap(PipelineUtils.getOrderForStages(dashboard));_
![dynamic](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/24286224/20c0de24-10af-11e7-85b9-5767caf88db4.png)

The dynamic pipeline service will be disabled in future? I think it's better than the pipeline service. wdquan1985
289028019 @wdquan1985  - sounds good. Have you tried removing "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled" from properties to see product dashboard, want to make sure both dynamic pipeline and pipeline service are working as expected.  nireeshT
289281073 @nireeshT - I had tried removing "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled" from properties, but it can't work as well as adding "feature.dynamicPipeline=enabled". Each of these stages shows the number of commits waiting to go to the next stage – amplifying the wait-times between the stages.  wdquan1985

Basically the idea is to build the pipeline dynamically with the data on hand as opposed to building it when the data is added as this has a number of problems (https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/804#issuecomment-247391585). Looks like that change you made adds in some missing logic that was added to the regular pipeline when custom names of environments were added. MarkRx

column2: When using docker to create a versionone collector, we found that there was no properties file was being created. This was due to a syntax error in the properties builder script when copying the values to the properties file. Once that file was created, the was no CRON being specified. CRON has been added to the versionone properties builder as well as the syntax errors being corrected.
column5: Fixed issues in version one properties builder shell file

column2: This PR adds a property to the main project POM to allow the docker maven plugin to use the host's ~/.docker/config.json file to authenticate to private registries. If none is specified when building images with maven, default value is false to maintain transparent backwards compatibility.
column5: Allow use of Docker Config JSON for private registry

curl --connect-timeout 10 -m 60 -i -X POST --header "Content-Type:application/json" -H "Accept:application/json" --data
'{"artifactName":"SANDBOX","canonicalName":"SANDBOX","artifactGroup":"SANDBOX","artifactVersion":"1.0","buildId":"timestamp","timestamp":1488942038335,"sourceChangeSet":[{"scmUrl":"http://127.0.0.1/gerrit/60730","scmBranch":"1.0","scmRevisionNumber":"Ica15fe4f1f9d05a3c6bf74b7c0df8191565fcf76","scmAuthor":"ZHANG,Harry(Harry)","scmParentRevisionNumbers":["d61cbc08f08bb8f674c41b4f55ff6e4fd784378d"],"type":"New","scmCommitTimestamp":1488963918000,"numberOfChanges":1}],"metadata":{"jobName":"SANDBOX","buildUrl":"127.0.0.1/job/SANDBOX/179/","buildNumber":179,"jobUrl":"http://127.0.0.1/job/SANDBOX/","instanceUrl":"http://127.0.0.1/"}}' -u userName:password http://127.0.0.1:8080/api/artifact .
I have send the username and password to hygieia, but there is an error:
_{"timestamp":1489558957506,"status":401,"error":"Unauthorized","message":"Full authentication is required to access this resource","path":"/api/artifact"}_
 
Then I permit the url request which start with api by changing code in the spring security java configuration file com.capitalone.dashboard.config.WebSecurityConfig.java.
	@Override
	protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
		http.headers().cacheControl();

			.authorizeRequests().antMatchers("/appinfo").permitAll()
								.antMatchers("/registerUser").permitAll()

                                                                _.antMatchers("/api**").permitAll()_
								.antMatchers(HttpMethod.GET, "/**").permitAll()			
								.anyRequest().authenticated()
									.and()
								.addFilterBefore(standardLoginRequestFilter(), UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class)
								.addFilterBefore(ldapLoginRequestFilter(), UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class)
								.addFilterBefore(jwtAuthenticationFilter, UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class)
								.exceptionHandling().authenticationEntryPoint(new Http401AuthenticationEntryPoint("Authorization"));
	}.

But it still can't work, how can I configure to ignore the authentication and authorization checks?

Hello,

I am currently working on creating a new template for dashboard. Where I want to have a dashboard with 6 sonarqube widgets and only those widgets and nothing else. I am working for a similar functionality for the rest of widgets too. So In short I am creating a template  with all the widgets as sonar widgets. So I want to have one sonarqube dashboard, one bamboo dashboard , udeploy dashboard etc.  

So i was able to create a template with all sonrqube widgets. The problem I am running into is the data in all the sonarqube widgets is getting reflected the same. If I select one sonarqube report in one sonarqube widget, the same same report is getting reflected in all the widgets. Here are my screenshots

The empty dashboard looks like this
![empty dashboard](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/26384694/23861568/d567632a-07e0-11e7-9ebf-8714467a3f4d.PNG)

I looked at the components collection in the database. Even though there are 6 code quality widgets in the dashboard. It only stores one code quality element in the collectorItems. This might me the reason for this.
![1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/26384694/23862127/9b76a124-07e2-11e7-91cb-024193c1a8fa.PNG)

Any inputs on this would be appreciated.

We've made an installation of Hygieia and everything seems to be working fine. But when an Sprint associated with an Issue is  closed or opened that information doesn't seem to be reflected in the MongoDB until that Issue gets modified.

I've seen that the UpdatedDate of the issues is not being changed when their associated Sprint get's opened or closed, and I guess that's the reason the "story.st" query doesn't return those issues and thus they are not updated.

I've being reading almost all the opened and closed issues in this GitHub project and I've not seen anything related with this.... Am I missing something obvious in Jira's/Hygieia configuration?

See below the relevant configuration options

```
feature.pageSize=100

feature.deltaStartDate=2016-02-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.masterStartDate=2016-02-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.deltaCollectorItemStartDate=2016-02-01T00:00:00.000000

feature.cron=0 */5 * * * *

feature.queryFolder=jiraapi-queries
feature.storyQuery=story
feature.epicQuery=epic

feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Epic,Feature,Story,Bug,Task
```

We have double checked that the custom_fields are properly configured.

Thanks!
column5: [JIRA] Sprint status not being updated
column11:
286256760 That is correct. The underlying model does not have "Sprint" types. Instead each issue stores information about the sprint directly. As a result as you have observed updates to the sprint data will only get reflected on issues if the issue also updates.

I would think in most situations this should not be an issue. If you are closing a sprint then all the issues should be removed from the sprint. In our jira instance sprints cannot be closed with open issues. If all of the issues are closed or moved back to the backlog they would end up being updated (the spring field change) and hence you would get the sprint data updated for free.

Those query settings refer to *.st files in the code at src/main/resources/jiraapi-queries. It might be possible to set the queryFolder property and point it to a mounted directory with custom *.st queries. I've never tried it though and that code has been there before I started working with Hygieia. MarkRx
286260241 Ok. I was just wondering if there was something we were missing, but If this is a known issue or just the expected behavior then I guess we will have to live with that :-).

In our instance issues are not being updated on sprint closed/activated actions, but that might be something we have not configured properly in Jira.

Thank you very much! alfonso-presa

column2:
The recursiveGetJobDetails added in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1038 for folder support makes a rest call for  every job inside a sub-folder. In other words, if jenkins at its root has 1 job and 1 folder with 10 jobs, this would result in 11 rest calls. For jenkins setups with lot of sub-folders, this would cause a performance issue.

Based on @tabladrum suggestion in the comments of https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1038, this has been changed to pull all the jobs upfront based on a folderDepth parameter that the user can set in the properties file.
The limitation of this approach is jobs inside folders deeper than folderDepth will not be collected.

resolves https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/582 and https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1187

@MarkRx Please take a look and try it out.
column5: Fix for jenkins collector performance with sub-folders.

p,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn],jobs[name,url,builds[number,url],lastSuccessfulBuild[timestamp,builtOn],lastBuild[timestamp,builtOn]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]]

This is problematic as the URL is too long. This can cause issues with load balancers, security scanners, proxies, etc. Also, building the build url should use some kind of reusable buffer. It's burning through Strings and wasting memory.

A better question to ask is why are we obtaining builds for all jobs right away? Can't we lazily obtain builds only when a job is enabled (selected)? Doing this would make the recursion in the example only use 2 rest calls. Furthermore in an enterprise instance of 1000's of jobs we will save a lot of resources by not obtaining builds for jobs we never intend to track. @tabladrum @satishc1  MarkRx
286278528 @MarkRx You could set the folderDepth to 25 and shorten the url length by half. Do you need a depth of 50? We talked about lazily loading the builds but the code as it is at present doesn't add jobs if there are no builds. From what we are seeing the recursiveGetJobDetails added in https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/pull/1038 is extremely slow due to the number of rest calls its making. In the test that you ran, did it work and if it did how was the performance compared to how you were doing the recursive calls initially.
 satishc1
286461726 @MarkRx @tabladrum Set default folderDepth to 10 after verifying its sufficient for how jenkins jobs are configured for us internally. Again, this is a parameter so you can choose to increase it based on how your jenkins folders are setup. Hopefully depths greater than 20 are an oddity and not the norm. satishc1
288396647 It appears to be working. I did encounter a stack overflow error but that may or may not be related - #1257. A default of 10 sounds fine. Please add it to the generated properties file consumed by docker. MarkRx
288822962 @MarkRx @tabladrum Cool. Thanks for testing it out. I updated the generated prop file for docker. Let me merge this and we'll see if we can recreate https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1257 . satishc1
