column2:
hi team,

i reffered one of the issue opened here for system requirement which mentioned system requirement as follows, **can you please also share what will be the minimum required disk space to be available?**:

Red Hat Enterprise Linux Server release 7.2 (Maipo)
Linux kernel 3.10.0-327.36.1.el7.x86_64
16GB Ram
The average RAM consumption will be 130 Mb for apache httpd. This will go up depending on how many users hit apache. These numbers are for light usage with about 10 people running the UI.
MongoDb 3.2.9 takes up about 1 Gb RAM.
The API process takes up about 1 Gb RAM.
On average each collector running will have RAM consumption of 1gb per collector.
column5: System requirement to setup hygieia on linux
column11:
285367245 @varundevopsid99  It will depend on whether you run all the modules on the same server or separate it out. Ui , api and collector modules will pretty much remain static except for log files that will grow.  The mongo data is the one you need to compute and plan for. A size of 20 to 30 Gb should be sufficient for mongo. satishc1
285416226 Thanks... Also can you let me know have you configured Docker on this linux setup?which version? and if possible can you share steps how you configured Hygieia setup in docker...thanks varundevopsid99

column11:
285360776 @krishs123  - when using Jenkins build collector look for below value in build.properties file. Change it to port used.
#Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
    jenkins.servers[0]=http://jenkins.company.com
 
If using Hygieia publisher , go to Jenkins -> Manage Jenkins -> Jenkins location section -> change the url with correct port value . 
 nireeshT

299895468 Here is an example sh script I use to setup a Jenkins build that hits an internal artifactory repository:

```
#!/bin/bash

rm -rf UI/node
mkdir UI/node

# Install node
if [ ! -f UI/node/node ]; then
  echo "Extracting node..."
  mkdir -p UI/node/tmp
  curl ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/tools/node/v5.4.1/node-v5.4.1-linux-x64.tar.gz | tar xz -C UI/node/tmp
  cp UI/node/tmp/node-v5.4.1-linux-x64/bin/node UI/node/node
  rm -rf UI/node/tmp
fi

# Install npm
if [ ! -f UI/node/npm ]; then
  echo "Extracting npm..."
  mkdir -p UI/node/node_modules/npm
  curl ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/tools/npm/npm-2.14.15.tgz | tar xz -C UI/node/node_modules/npm --strip-components 1
  cp UI/node/node_modules/npm/bin/npm UI/node/npm
  
  # Install artifactory resolver
  export PATH=$PATH:$WORKSPACE/UI/node/
  UI/node/npm install bower-art-resolver
fi

echo "Creating .npmrc..."
cat > UI/.npmrc <<EOL
registry = ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/api/npm/npm
phantomjs_cdnurl = ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/tools/phantomjs/
EOL

echo "Creating .bowerrc..."
cat > UI/.bowerrc <<EOL
{
  "proxy": "<myproxy>",
  "https-proxy": "<myproxy>",
  "registry": "${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/api/bower/bower",
    "resolvers": [
      "bower-art-resolver"
    ]
}
EOL
``` MarkRx

299895468 Here is an example sh script I use to setup a Jenkins build that hits an internal artifactory repository:

```
#!/bin/bash

rm -rf UI/node
mkdir UI/node

# Install node
if [ ! -f UI/node/node ]; then
  echo "Extracting node..."
  mkdir -p UI/node/tmp
  curl ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/tools/node/v5.4.1/node-v5.4.1-linux-x64.tar.gz | tar xz -C UI/node/tmp
  cp UI/node/tmp/node-v5.4.1-linux-x64/bin/node UI/node/node
  rm -rf UI/node/tmp
fi

# Install npm
if [ ! -f UI/node/npm ]; then
  echo "Extracting npm..."
  mkdir -p UI/node/node_modules/npm
  curl ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/tools/npm/npm-2.14.15.tgz | tar xz -C UI/node/node_modules/npm --strip-components 1
  cp UI/node/node_modules/npm/bin/npm UI/node/npm
  
  # Install artifactory resolver
  export PATH=$PATH:$WORKSPACE/UI/node/
  UI/node/npm install bower-art-resolver
fi

echo "Creating .npmrc..."
cat > UI/.npmrc <<EOL
registry = ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/api/npm/npm
phantomjs_cdnurl = ${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/tools/phantomjs/
EOL

echo "Creating .bowerrc..."
cat > UI/.bowerrc <<EOL
{
  "proxy": "<myproxy>",
  "https-proxy": "<myproxy>",
  "registry": "${ARTIFACTORY_URL}/api/bower/bower",
    "resolvers": [
      "bower-art-resolver"
    ]
}
EOL
``` MarkRx

column2:
![latest_build](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15209842/23534178/0e7a9990-fff1-11e6-8aa0-ec7ac7e715c5.png)
After a new build info has been imported to hygieia server, the build stage will make a request, such as http://localhost:3000/api/build/?componentId=58aba84b22b4042344b9ac6c&endDateBegins=1488258758706&endDateEnds=1488357136355, to update the latest build number. If the time of jenkins server is earlier than hygieia server, the endTime of the new build info should be earlier than endDateBegins which always use the current time of hygieia server, so the request will never get any info, the latest build number can't be updated.
In order to avoid this issue, I suggest using the endTime of the new build info as the endDateBegins.
column5: The latest build number in the pipeline build stage can't be updated.

I am running Jenkins and Hygieia in a docker compose setup. The dashboard is fully functional, with UI and API communicating correctly through `http://hygieia-api:8080/api`. However, when I configure the Jenkins plugin using this same URL and test the connection, I get a 500 with `A RequestDispatcher could not be located for the default servlet 'api'`.

I assume that means that I can reach the API server from Jenkins, but I can't guess much more...

284758381 Jenkins is running in port 8080 and it is not exposed outside the container, as I have nginx in front.

The relevant docker-compose.yml parts are:

```yml
version: '2'
services:
  nginx:
    image: "nginx:latest"
    container_name: nginx
    ports:
      - 80:80
      - 443:443
    networks:
      cinet:
        ipv4_address: 10.10.1.20
    depends_on:
      - hygieia-ui
      - sonarqube
      - jenkins
    volumes:
      - ./data_nginx:/etc/nginx/conf.d:ro
  jenkins:
    build:
      context: ./dockerfiles/jenkins
      args:
        - http_proxy
        - https_proxy
        - no_proxy
    container_name: jenkins
    networks:
      - cinet
    privileged: true
    volumes:
      - ./data_jenkins:/var/jenkins_home
      - /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock
      - /usr/bin/docker:/usr/bin/docker
    environment:
      DOCKER_SOCKET: /var/run/docker.sock
      DOCKER_GROUP: dockerhost
      JENKINS_USER: jenkins
      DOCKER_HOST: unix:///var/run/docker.sock
      http_proxy: ****
      https_proxy: ****
      no_proxy: ****
      JAVA_OPTS: ##Proxy setup here

  mongodb:
    image: mongo:latest
    container_name: hygieia-db
    command: mongod --smallfiles
    networks:
      - cinet
    volumes:
      - ./data_hygieia/mongo:/data/db:rw
  hygieia-api:
    image: capitaloneio/hygieia-api:latest
    container_name: hygieia-api
    networks:
      - cinet
    volumes:
      - ./data_hygieia/logs:/hygieia/logs
    depends_on:
      - mongodb
    links:
      - mongodb:mongo
    environment:
      SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST: mongo
      SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT: 27017
      SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE: dashboard
      SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME: mongo
      SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD: ******
  hygieia-ui:
    image: capitaloneio/hygieia-ui:latest
    container_name: hygieia-ui
    networks:
      - cinet
    depends_on:
      - hygieia-api
    environment:
      HYGIEIA_API_PORT: http://hygieia-api:8080
networks:
  cinet:
    driver: bridge
    ipam:
      config:
        - subnet: 10.10.1.0/25
          gateway: 10.10.1.1

``` guillermonoainquantion

283056840 @gauravjos If inside a proxy try using a .bowerrc file. Refer to https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/823 satishc1
284011170 @gauravjos Closed. Reopen if still an issue.
If you are inside a proxy make sure your env vars are set. And use a .bowerrc file as mentioned before.
export http_proxy=http://yourproxyhost:yourproxyport
export https_proxy=https://yourproxyhost:yourproxyport

export HTTP_PROXY=http://yourproxyhost:yourproxyport
export HTTPS_PROXY=https://yourproxyhost:yourproxyport

export all_proxy=http://yourproxyhost:yourproxyport
export ALL_PROXY=http://yourproxyhost:yourproxyport satishc1

column5: Hygieia should be capable of fetching data using dates
column11:
282572734 While technically it is possible to store data for longer time, we intentionally kept it for 14 days for one reason: From DevOps/Agile perspective, 14 days i.e., sprint cycle is what should matter in terms of fast feedback to developers.

Note that the data actually don't get purged off. It's the UI which restricts displaying the data. 

However, an analytics aspect of all these is a fair ask and we do have the same internally. For analytical solution, you could replicate the data on to a separate MongoDB instance and run your preferred analytics tool on that. 

On the product dashboard page, you do have a view to 90 days trend on few metrics such as code quality, build break MTR, security vulnerability etc. We are planning to add more on that area. 

Would love to hear what others think. tabladrum
282577035 Thank you for your response.
I totally agree with you,DevOps/Agile perspective, 14 days i.e., sprint cycle is what matter and I know that data is not puffed off. But what I was trying to tell is suppose in team dashboard if a option is ther to select from and to date like,
FROM: Jan 1, 2017  TO Jan 14, 2017 
and view those data in team dashboard it would be good. 
Thanks. shilpsl1
289778894 @shilpsl1 Closed. satishc1

The current state of the docker-compose file results in exceptions when attempting to run API. See below. The docker-compose API should not default to requiring Jasypt. Right now it does because the docker image is build with "ENV SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD=ENC(aSPTk36yA/ZklUg75CrZ8w==)" which I presume is "password" encrypted with a key of "hygieiasecret".

The following should be done:
- There should be a way to run without Jasypt. Right now I can't start my collectors with docker-compose (without overriding commands) because the docker images do not have jasypt.encryptor.password. It seems this property is required even if I am not using ENC. It could be defaulted to "unencrypted" in the code perhaps.
- The 5 ENV commands in the Dockerfile should be removed. None of the other Dockerfiles contain these.
- ~~All of the other collectors should support automatically setting -Djasypt.encryptor.password if set using the same mechanism as the API.~~ The JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_SECRET variable should be removed along with -Djasypt.encryptor.password=$JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_SECRET. Spring will automatically set jasypt.encryptor.password if JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_PASSWORD is set.
- Starting the jira collector requires the JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_PASSWORD (equal to jasypt.encryptor.password) to be set to "hygieiasecret" even through I am not using ENC. Why?

```
hygieia-api:
  image: hygieia-api:latest
  container_name: hygieia-api
  ports:
  - "8080:8080"
  volumes:
  - ./logs:/hygieia/logs
  environment:
  - MONGO_PORT=tcp://10.0.2.2:27017
  - SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE=dashboard
  - FEATURE_DYNAMIC_PIPELINE=enabled
```

If I add a JASYPT_ENCRYPTOR_SECRET and set the JASYPT_ENTRYPTOR_SECRET:

column5: jira-collector properties
column11:
284181318 Could you edit your issue so that it isn't one giant header? It'll make it more readable. Do you use Docker or do you want to run Hygieia on a normal server?

Additionally not all of the fields are required. Basically find which you want to use. Some might not be available on your Jira instance. To check if one is available get an issue key and open the following URL in a browser, making sure to change the Jira domain and the issue name with your values: `https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]` ebosveld
289685652 @ebosveld What is meant by [some-issue-name] ? charan1011
330890962 @charan1011 :  Like mentioned above, not all the fields are required. You need to set the ones you need. 
[some-issue-name] is the title of issue in Jira board. nitin1706
